PART B: Apollonian Scaling Prediction for p6
========================================================================

IMPORTANT: This is a PREDICTION, not a certified theorem.
  - p6 has NOT been computed by this pipeline.
  - The Apollonian scaling rule is a heuristic conjecture.
  - The computation below is arithmetically faithful.
  - Results are labeled PREDICTED where applicable.

Apollonian gasket Hausdorff dimension D = 1.30568673
  (Boyd 1982; McMullen 1998; Numerical value: 1.30568673...)
  Source: well-known constant, not computed here.

Certified M4 parent: p5 = 3993746143633
  log(p5) = 29.01575079  (mpmath 100 dps)
  C_p5 = log(p5)*p5/(p5-1) = 29.01575079
  C(S5) = 40.437899478459  [M10 SHA ab9ce40c...]

Apollonian scaling rule: log(p_{n+1}) ~ log(p_n) + (log(p_n))^(1/D)

  Increment = (log p5)^(1/D) = 29.015751^(1/1.30568673)
            = 29.015751^0.76588050
            = 13.188722

  PREDICTED: log(p6) = 29.015751 + 13.188722 = 42.204473
  PREDICTED: p6      = e^42.2045 ~ 2.1339e+18
  PREDICTED: p6/p5   = e^13.1887 ~ 534305

  PREDICTED: C(p6) = log(p6)*p6/(p6-1) ~ 42.204473
  [Note: p6/(p6-1) -> 1 as p6 -> infinity; C(p6) ~ log(p6) = 42.204473]

  PREDICTED: C(S6) = C(S5) + C(p6)
           = 40.437899 + 42.204473
           = 82.642372

  PREDICTED g bound: g <= floor(C(S6)^2 / 4)
           = floor(82.6424^2 / 4)
           = floor(6829.7617 / 4)
           = floor(1707.4404) = 1707 -> g_max = 1708

  Checking external claim: C(S6) > 2*sqrt(1707) = 2*sqrt(1707)?
    2*sqrt(1707) = 82.631713
    C(S6) [predicted] = 82.642372
    Margin = 0.010659  (PASS with THIN margin)

CONDITIONAL THEOREM (certified arithmetic, heuristic premise):
  IF:  (1) The Apollonian scaling rule gives log(p6) correctly to 0.001
        (2) p6 is in S_{beta_0} = S_4 with the 6th element
  THEN: C(S6) = 82.6424 > 2*sqrt(1707) = 82.6317
  THEN: BC bound certifies RH for X_0(N) with genus g <= 1707

  Caveat: The IF conditions are strong heuristic assumptions, NOT theorems.
  The pipeline certifies the arithmetic; the interpretation is a conjecture.

